  "prompt": "What is the Romeo and Juliet law?",
  "response": "The Romeo and Juliet law is a legal provision designed to protect teenagers who engage in consensual sexual activity from being prosecuted for statutory rape, even if one or both partners are below the age of consent. These laws typically reduce or eliminate criminal penalties for consensual sexual activity between young people who are close in age.\n\nThe specifics of Romeo and Juliet laws vary by state, but they generally:\n\n1. Provide an age-related defense against statutory rape charges\n2. Apply when both parties are teenagers or young adults\n3. Have a specific age difference requirement (often around 2-4 years)\n4. Prevent a person from being labeled a sex offender for consensual activity\n\nThe goal is to prevent harsh legal consequences for young people engaging in consensual sexual activity with someone close to their own age.\n\nNot all states have Romeo and Juliet laws, and the details differ where they do exist. It's important to understand the specific regulations in your jurisdiction.",
